Things like this e.g. :
(from: https://github.com/junit-pioneer/junit-pioneer/pull/285/files )

		// This check is by purpose to throw an IAE.
		// E.g. Objects.requireNonNull(T value, String message) throws a NPE,
		// which has a total different meaning.
		if (null == methodParameterTypes) {
			throw new IllegalArgumentException("methodParameterTypes must not be null");
		}


Did you consider Objects.requireNonNull(T value, String message)? I think it conveys the same intent really nicely.


Yes, but it throws an NullPointerException and not an IllegalArgumentException. A NPE has a total different meaning than a IAE.
